Gravity Defied — Android (modernized)
======================================

This work is a modified version of the upstream Android port at
https://github.com/evgenyzinoviev/gravitydefied
baseline commit ee26c95fddff87826cfba7bfcdda6bac156c8741 ("Add GPLv2 license",
2015-08-14), imported on 2026-05-09.

Upstream is licensed under GPL v2; this work continues under GPL v2 — see
LICENSE.txt.

This NOTICE is the GPLv2 §2(a) "modification notice" for the work as a whole.
Per-commit detail lives in this repository's git history; this file lists the
categories of change made relative to upstream.


Modifications relative to upstream
----------------------------------

Build system
- Migrated from Eclipse / Ant to Android Studio + Gradle.
- Build scripts converted to Kotlin DSL (build.gradle.kts,
  settings.gradle.kts).
- compileSdk / targetSdk raised to current stable; minSdk raised from 8 to 23.

Dependencies
- Migrated to AndroidX; legacy android.support.* removed.
- ACRA crash reporter (acra-4.5.0.jar) removed; no replacement.
- All bare jars in libs/ removed in favour of Gradle-managed dependencies.

Manifest / permissions
- WRITE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE removed (no longer needed under scoped storage).
- android.hardware.gamepad declared as optional feature.
- Runtime permission flow added where required by API 23+.

Storage
- Replaced direct java.io.File access to external storage with the Storage
  Access Framework (ACTION_OPEN_DOCUMENT_TREE, persistable URI permissions,
  DocumentFile / ContentResolver). User picks the levels folder on first run;
  the folder survives uninstall and is visible in any file manager.
- Levels loader and download/install paths refactored against a small
  storage abstraction.

Platform API replacements
- Replaced deprecated Activity.onBackPressed override with
  OnBackPressedDispatcher / OnBackPressedCallback.
- Replaced deprecated startActivityForResult / onActivityResult call sites
  where appropriate.
- Replaced removed org.apache.http.* networking calls with HttpURLConnection.

Network calls
- Outbound API surface narrowed to what the user explicitly initiates: the
  level browser ("Download levels" → API.getLevels) and the per-level .mrg
  download (API.downloadMrg). The remaining three upstream endpoints, all
  of which fired without user action, were dropped:
    * getNotifications — fetched on every cold start; could pop a
      server-supplied dialog and open a server-supplied URL.
    * sendStats — posted a per-installation UUID plus per-level completion
      stats on a timer.
    * sendKeyboardLogs — debug-only menu item that posted the touch-input
      log buffer with the device manufacturer/model string.
  The companion plumbing went with them: the Installation UUID generator
  (org.happysanta.gd.Installation, originally org.acra.util.Installation),
  the last_send_stats preference, the keyboard-log buffer in
  KeyboardController, the dev.gdtr.net debug endpoint, and the API
  version-handshake parameter. Motivation is twofold: no app data leaves
  the device unless the player asks for a level list or a download, and
  the upstream-operated gdtr.net endpoint (we don't run it) only sees
  requests that actually deliver content to the user.

Input
- Added physical gamepad / controller support
  (org.happysanta.gd.ControllerInputHandler): d-pad, left stick, A/B,
  Start, with semantic mapping that follows the active keyset in-game and
  the canonical menu-nav keys in menu.
- Added analog channel into the physics engine (Physics._aIIVAnalog)
  alongside the existing digital-numpad-key path. Left stick on a
  physical gamepad now drives throttle / brake / lean proportional to
  deflection: half-tilt produces visibly less torque or engine response
  than full-tilt. Sign convention matches the original digital path
  (stick up = accel, down = brake, left/right = lean), and keyboard /
  on-screen keypad / d-pad / touch virtual-d-pad continue to take the
  digital path with implicit full magnitude — no perceived change for
  any non-stick input. Stick deadzone is configurable via a new
  "Stick deadzone" option (Precise / Default / Forgiving / Very
  forgiving); default 15% matches the value the analog channel
  shipped with originally. A separate "Stick mode" option toggles
  the analog magnitude path off entirely (Analog / Digital) — Digital
  snaps each axis past the deadzone to ±1 / 0 so the stick behaves
  like the d-pad while still going through the analog channel.
  "Stick layout" option (Single / Dual lean-L gas-R / Dual gas-L
  lean-R) optionally routes throttle and lean to separate physical
  sticks so the player can adjust both simultaneously without thumb
  conflict; right stick axes auto-resolved per device (AXIS_Z/AXIS_RZ
  or AXIS_RX/AXIS_RY, whichever the pad declares as bipolar via
  InputDevice.getMotionRange), so both common conventions work
  without user calibration; in dual modes each stick is treated as
  1D (its other axis ignored entirely, including for the deadzone
  check) so drift on the unused axis can never leak into physics.
  Default Single preserves the original one-stick behaviour.
  Two transforms compose with the layout, both per source stick:
  "Stick invert" (None / Left / Right / All) flips the sign of the
  affected stick's post-scale output; "Stick X/Y swap" (None / Left
  / Right / Both) swaps which physical axis on the affected stick
  feeds the physics quantity the layout assigns to it. In Single
  mode the right-stick toggles are no-ops. Both default to None.
- Analog input drives the rider's visual posture proportionally:
  the rest-length presets (Physics m_Hak[*].m_forI) and the visual
  lean accumulator (m_TI) are now lerped between neutral and the
  fully-leaned target by the analog magnitude, so partial stick
  deflection produces a partial lean rather than snapping to the
  extreme posture as the original categorical assignment did.
  Digital input still resolves to the full preset bit-for-bit.
- Per-axis input merge: digital input (keyboard / on-screen keypad /
  controller buttons / touch virtual-d-pad) takes priority over the
  analog stick on whichever physics axis it touches, while the other
  axis continues to read from the stick. Implemented in
  GameView.applyMergedInput so all input paths funnel through a
  single merge point. Lets the player hold a button for full gas /
  brake while the stick still drives lean (and vice versa).
- On-screen keypad reworked: bottom-anchored in both orientations
  (single strip in portrait, two corner clusters in landscape), with new
  user setting "Auto-hide keypad after" (Show / Hide / 5/10/15/30s)
  driven by a touch-idle timer. "Hide" is a hard off-switch — keypad
  never shows (in menu or in-game) and touch does not wake it, so
  controller-only players don't have the keypad obscure menu items
  or steal scroll gestures.

Display
- Added optional "Immersive mode" setting that hides the status bar (nav bar
  unaffected) via WindowInsetsControllerCompat with
  BEHAVIOR_SHOW_TRANSIENT_BARS_BY_SWIPE so users can swipe to peek the bar
  back. Default off.
- Added "Sky" theme system (replaces the previous binary "Dark mode"
  toggle): picks the colors painted as the in-game sky and the menu
  chrome background. Each preset is a *theme* defined by a primary
  and a secondary ARGB; built-in presets pair each primary with a
  curated complementary secondary so LINEAR / CENTRAL gradient
  modes read as natural atmospheric transitions (twilight, sunset,
  dawn, etc.) instead of a solid wash. 16 built-in options — Black, Dark gray, Dark
  teal, Mid teal, Blue, Indigo, Forest, Burgundy, Light teal, Cyan,
  Sky blue, Lavender, Salmon, Mint, Light gray, White — plus 3
  user-editable Custom slots (Custom 1/2/3) that each store
  independent primary R/G/B and secondary R/G/B (6 channels per
  slot, same pattern as Track and Neon Custom slots). Built-in
  palette is split 8 dark / 8 light, curated as dark↔light pairs
  (Black↔White, Dark gray↔Light gray, teals, Blue↔Sky blue, Indigo↔
  Lavender, Forest↔Mint, Burgundy↔Salmon) and grouped darker-to-
  lighter top to bottom. A separate
  "Sky gradient" mode picker (6 options — Solid / Secondary / Linear
  / Reverse linear / Central / Reverse central) controls how primary
  and secondary combine in the in-game sky: Solid paints primary
  only (default — matches upstream), Secondary paints secondary
  only, Linear/Reverse Linear paint a vertical gradient between
  primary and secondary, Central/Reverse Central paint a radial
  gradient centered on the screen. Built-in presets render
  identically across all gradient modes (primary = secondary);
  Custom slots are where gradient modes become visually distinct.
  The in-game sky paint is built via a strategy dispatch in
  GameView with a lazy Paint+Shader cache keyed on (mode, primary,
  secondary, width, height) — no per-frame allocation, shader
  rebuilt only on user setting change or rotation. The dispatch
  shape is deliberately extensible: a future "image background"
  mode would slot in as one additional case loading a Bitmap.
  The "is the sky dark?" classification consumed by every dark-
  aware render/chrome path (sprite tint, BW track contrast, HUD
  progress bar, system bar icon tint, AlertDialog Material Dark
  theme, on-screen keypad row tinting) is now derived from the
  chosen sky preset's *primary* BT.601 luma — keys off primary
  (not secondary) so the chrome doesn't flicker when only the
  gradient mode changes. Menu chrome stays *solid* (always paints
  primary only — no gradient on menu screens) for legibility; the
  gradient is a scenery feature that belongs behind the demo /
  gameplay only. Menu text stays pure white on any "dark" sky and
  pure black on any "light" sky for maximum contrast. Single
  source of truth via Settings.getMenuBgColor / getMenuFgColor /
  getMenuItemColorStateList; the static R.drawable.menu_item_color
  selector was replaced with a programmatic ColorStateList that
  follows the selector. In-game render path also participates:
  GameView.setColor() lifts structural near-black inputs (line
  wheels, driver body lines) toward a soft light gray
  via a brighten ramp when the sky is dark; sprite wheels are
  tinted via a cached ColorMatrixColorFilter that brightens dark
  source pixels toward a target offset while leaving AA edges
  intact; on-screen keypad row backgrounds and digit text pull
  from Settings so they follow the selector. Default White +
  Solid gradient — preserves upstream's light look bit-for-bit.
  Legacy dark_mode_enabled pref is migrated once on first run
  after upgrade (true → Black, false → White). A separate "Bike
  tint" option (Colors → Bike submenu) overrides the auto-derived
  default for the bike — 19 options grouped as Auto / Natural /
  4 grayscale (Dark / Medium / Light / White) / 10 colored (Red /
  Orange / Gold / Green / Teal / Cyan / Blue / Purple / Magenta /
  Pink, ordered around the color wheel) / 3 Custom slots
  (user-editable RGB). The
  brighten formula generalizes from a single grayscale offset to a
  per-channel target — the same matrix shape lifts blacks toward
  any color while leaving AA edges near-white, so colored tints
  read as a tinted silhouette rather than a wash. Both render
  paths consume the same Settings.getBikeTintRgb() so the sprited
  bike (ColorMatrix on the wheel bitmap) and the line-art bike
  (per-channel slope+offset in setColor's near-black branch) stay
  visually consistent — picking Red tints both. Start and finish
  flag poles get their own independent color settings under a new
  Colors → Flags sub-screen, each with the same shape as Bike tint
  (Auto + 15 built-in hues — 3 neutrals plus 12 chromatic walking
  the color wheel from Red through Brown — plus 3 user-editable
  Custom slots, per pole).
  Flag poles bypass setColor()'s near-black branch — they paint
  directly via paint.setColor(Settings.getStartFlagArgb()) so the
  user's Bike tint choice no longer bleeds into the structural pole
  lines (a Red bike no longer turns the flag poles red). Auto
  preserves the upstream "structural line" behavior, following
  Settings.getMenuFgColor(). The Colors submenu is itself
  organized into four sub-screens — Track, Bike, Sky, Flags —
  each holding the preset picker, gradient/fill options where
  applicable, the per-channel RGB editors for Custom slots, and an
  inline copy-into-Custom chooser that snapshots the active preset's
  channels into the picked slot and switches to it.
- Splash screen logo PNGs (codebrew.png, gd.png across mdpi / hdpi /
  xhdpi) re-encoded with proper alpha. Upstream's PNGs were opaque
  white rectangles with the black artwork drawn on top — the surround
  pixels were RGB (255,255,255) at alpha 255 (or no alpha channel at
  all in the RGB-mode files). This presented the brand marks inside a
  visible white "card" against the sky-themed backdrop in light themes,
  and a black card in dark themes (the splash invert filter flipped
  the white surround to black along with the artwork). The PNGs are
  now true black-on-transparent with alpha derived from per-pixel
  luminance (`alpha = 255 - min(r,g,b)`) so antialiased edges blend
  cleanly into whatever sky color sits behind them. The splash render
  code itself is unchanged: the loading backdrop still tracks
  `Settings.getMenuBgColor()` and `getSplashInvertPaint()` still
  inverts the (now alpha-shaped) artwork to white when dark mode is
  on, so legibility is preserved on dark themes.
- AlertDialog construction routed through a single Helpers.makeAlertBuilder
  helper that wraps the context with Theme.Material.Dialog.Alert when the
  chosen sky classifies as dark, so system dialogs (load-confirm, score-reset,
  download prompts, sort picker, etc.) follow the app theme instead of
  inheriting the activity's legacy light NoTitleBar theme.
- Added optional "Show FPS" diagnostic overlay: top-right corner of the
  in-game view, mirroring the existing timer's font and color, displaying
  the average per-frame interval in milliseconds and the derived frame
  rate ("X.Xms / Yfps") sampled over the last 30 onDraw calls. Default
  off.

Gameplay visuals
- Driver-shadow option widened from a boolean (Off/On) to a tri-state
  (Off / Shadow / Neon). Shadow is the original gray fade; Neon re-uses
  the same render path but inverts the brightness ramp — close to ground
  glows in the active neon base color, fading to a dark gray (#363636)
  as the bike rises. The actual hue used by Neon is picked separately
  via a dedicated "Neon color" setting under the Colors submenu (Yellow,
  Red, Purple, Blue, Cyan, Green, plus three user-editable Custom
  slots). Default stays "Shadow" so the original behavior is preserved.
  One-shot migration translates pre-collapse shadow_mode values 2..7
  (the old per-color neons) into shadow_mode=Neon + the matching
  NEON_COLOR_*, so existing players keep their previously selected
  combination across the upgrade.
- Track render reworked to a uniform 3-line path used by every color
  preset. Each segment draws: foreground = the lower / brighter line on
  the actual ground points, background = the upper / darker line on the
  raised perspective projection (also the raised end of an across tick
  rendered as a smooth foreground→background gradient). Replaces the
  upstream 2-line raised+across-tick render. Default Original carries
  the two upstream greens with the brighter one as foreground
  (#00FF00 / #00AA00), so the default Solid render matches upstream's
  flat-track bright green. Other presets available are Cyan / Red /
  Yellow / Lime / Blue / Gray / Black/White. Black/White is theme-aware
  (foreground white in dark mode, black in light mode; background
  always darker than foreground).
- Perspective-mode area fill added: configurable fill for the region
  between the ground contour and the raised perspective projection.
  Five modes — Off (default; wireframe, preserves upstream visual) /
  Foreground / Background / Third (a curated per-preset color, editable
  R/G/B for Custom slots) / Gradient (foreground→background strip-fill
  matching the across-tick interpolation direction). Implemented as an
  allocation-free path render in GameView (reused Path / Paint; gradient
  uses N trapezoidal strips with colors pre-interpolated via the same
  interpArgb path the across ticks already use, so no shader and no
  per-frame allocation in the hot path). N is exposed as a "Gradient
  steps" option (2/3/4/6/8/12, default 12 — the smoothest band count
  on the list; lower values are still selectable for chunkier banding
  or perf-constrained devices) and drives the across-tick
  rib subdivision count too so the rib's color steps stay aligned with
  the strip boundaries regardless of setting. Independently, the
  across-tick ribs are togglable via a new "Across ticks" option (On
  default, preserves upstream visual) so the user can pick wireframe /
  fill only / ribbed-over-fill combinations.

- Map color gradient option added (Solid / Gradient / Reversed) —
  applies to every preset including Original. Solid ignores the
  background color and draws every line of the render in foreground
  (the across "gradient" degenerates to a solid foreground tick), so
  the render is effectively single-color even with perspective on.
  Gradient is the canonical 3-line render with a foreground→background
  across gradient. Reversed swaps foreground and background so the
  brighter line moves onto the raised projection — and dims the
  perspective-off line too (it uses background when reversed). Default
  Solid keeps a single-color track look out of the box. A previous
  standalone "Green" preset was removed in the same change — Original
  carries the upstream green pair so a green-themed track gradient is
  still reachable via Original + Gradient.

- Colors submenu added under Options consolidating every color-related
  setting in one place: Track color preset (now 10 built-ins + 3
  user-editable Custom slots — adds Orange and Magenta to round out
  the warm/cool spectrum), Map color gradient toggle, six in-place
  editable RGB channel rows (FG R/G/B + BG R/G/B) for the active track
  preset, Neon color preset (8 built-in hues + 3 Custom slots — adds
  Orange between Yellow and Red, plus White for a universal glow), three
  in-place editable RGB rows for the active neon preset, and two
  "Copy preset into Custom…" actions that snapshot the active preset's
  channels into a chosen Custom slot. Editing on a channel row uses an
  in-place 3-digit cursor (UP/DOWN cycle digit 0–9, LEFT/RIGHT move,
  FIRE advances/exits) modeled on the high-score name entry; assembled
  values clamp to 255 on exit. Selecting a channel row while a built-in
  preset is active routes to the copy-into-Custom chooser instead of
  entering edit mode, so the built-in palettes stay read-only. Works
  with touch, on-screen keypad, physical keyboard, and gamepad
  identically; the Colors screen overrides UP/DOWN routing locally so
  digit cycling reaches the highlighted row while in edit mode without
  losing list navigation otherwise.

- OptionsMenuElement gained an opt-in list-picker mode for long
  cycles. The class already constructed an auto-generated subscreen
  with one row per option (used previously only as a fallback);
  setting useListPicker=true wires KEY_FIRE to push that subscreen
  with the current value pre-highlighted instead of cycling
  selection in-place. LEFT/RIGHT keep the in-place nudge for
  power-user one-shots. Enabled on the three long-cycle pickers
  (Track 13, Neon 11, Sky 19 options) where cycling past every
  option was tedious; short cycles (≤6 options like gradient mode,
  fill mode, stick layout, on/off toggles) stay in-place where the
  cycle is faster than a screen push/pop. Parent click handlers
  remain unchanged — _charvZ() returns false in list mode so the
  handler reads the freshly-picked value and runs its side effects
  (Settings.setX, applyDarkMode, refresh channel rows) without
  advancing the cycle.

Other
- Cosmetic / clarity comments added at sites where an API change forced a
  code change, noting the old call and why it changed (helps cross-checking
  against upstream).
